<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.css.cornell.edu/faculty/lehmann/terra_preta/TerraPretahome.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.css.cornell.edu/faculty/lehmann/terra_preta/TerraPretahome.htm" rel="nofollow"><i>Terra Preta de Indio</i></a>, Lehmann, Johannes, in Soil Biochemistry (internal citations omitted); <i>see also</i> <a href="http://www.biochar-international.org/images/NZSR64_1_Winsley.pdf" class="external text" title="http://www.biochar-international.org/images/NZSR64_1_Winsley.pdf" rel="nofollow"><i>Biochar and Bioenergy Production for Climate Change Mitigation</i></a>, Winsley, Peter, 64 New Zealand Sci. Review. 5, 5 (2007); Kern, Dirse C.,<i>New Dark Earth Experiment in the Tailandia City – Para-Brazil: The Dream of Wim Sombroek</i>, 18th World Congress of Soil Science (9-15 July 2006). Not only do biochar-enriched soils contain more carbon, 150gC/kg compared to 20-30gC/kg in surrounding soils, but biochar-enriched soils are, on average, more than twice as deep as surrounding soils. Therefore, the total carbon stored in these soils can be one order of magnitude higher than adjacent soils. <i>See id</i></li>
